GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 270
Short Title: Revise Law on the Death Penalty. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Willis, Pyrtle, Miller, and Ward (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Judiciary 2, if favorable, State and Local Government, if favorable, Rules,
Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 5, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REVISE THE METHODS OF EXECUTION AVAILABLE FOR A PERSON
3 CONVICTED OF A CRIMINAL OFFENSE AND SENTENCED TO DEATH.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 15-187 is repealed.
6 SECTION 2. G.S. 15-188 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 15-188. Manner and place of execution.
8 (a) Any person convicted of a criminal offense and sentenced to death shall be executed
9 in accordance with this section and the remainder of this Article. The warden of Central Prison
10 may obtain and employ the drugs necessary to carry out the provisions of this Article, regardless
11 of contrary provisions in Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
12 (b) In accordance with G.S. 15-187, the mode of executing a death sentence must in every
13 case be by administering to the convict or felon an intravenous injection of a substance or
14 substances in a lethal quantity sufficient to cause death and until the person is dead, and that
15 procedure shall be determined by the Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction, who shall
16 ensure compliance with the federal and State constitutions; and when any person, convict or felon
17 shall be sentenced by any court of the State having competent jurisdiction to be so executed, the
18 punishment shall only be inflicted within a permanent death chamber which the superintendent
19 of the State penitentiary is hereby authorized and directed to provide within the walls of the North
20 Carolina penitentiary at Raleigh, North Carolina. A person convicted of a criminal offense and
21 sentenced to death shall be executed by electrocution or, at the election of the convicted person,
22 by firing squad or lethal injection, if it is available at the time of election, under the direction of
23 the Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction. The election for death by electrocution,
24 firing squad, or lethal injection must be made in writing 14 days before each execution date or it
25 is waived. If the convicted person receives a stay of execution or the execution date has passed
26 for any reason, then the election expires and must be renewed in writing 14 days before a new
27 execution date. If the convicted person waives the right of election, then the penalty must be
28 administered by electrocution.
29 (c) If the mode of executing a death sentence is by lethal injection, the warden of Central
30 Prison may obtain and employ the drugs necessary to carry out the provisions of this Article,
31 regardless of contrary provisions in Chapter 90 of the General Statutes. The superintendent of
32 the State penitentiary shall also cause to be provided, in conformity with this Article, the
33 necessary appliances for the infliction of the punishment of death and qualified personnel to set
34 up and prepare the injection, administer the preinjections, insert the IV catheter, and to perform
*H270-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 other tasks required for this procedure in accordance with the requirements of this
2 Article.appliances.
3 (d) Upon receipt of the notice of execution, the Secretary of the Department of Adult
4 Correction shall determine and certify by affidavit under penalty of perjury to the North Carolina
5 Supreme Court whether the methods provided in subsection (a) of this section are available.
6 (e) A person convicted of a capital crime and sentenced to death prior to the effective
7 date of this section must be administered death by electrocution, unless the person elects death
8 by firing squad or lethal injection, if it is available, in writing 14 days before the execution date.
9 (f) If execution by lethal injection under this section is determined and certified pursuant
10 to subsection (d) of this section to be unavailable by the Secretary of the Department of Adult
11 Correction or is held to be unconstitutional by an appellate court of competent jurisdiction, then
12 the manner of inflicting a death sentence must be by electrocution, unless the convicted person
13 elects death by firing squad.
14 (g) The execution shall only be administered within a permanent death chamber which
15 the superintendent of the State penitentiary is hereby authorized and directed to provide within
16 the walls of the North Carolina penitentiary at Raleigh, North Carolina.
17 (h) The Department of Adult Correction shall provide written notice to a convicted
18 person of the person's right to election under this section and the available methods.
19 (i) The Department of Adult Correction shall establish protocols and procedures for
20 carrying out executions pursuant to this section."
21 SECTION 3. G.S. 15-188.1 reads as rewritten:
22 "§ 15-188.1. Health care professional assistance.
23 (a) Any assistance rendered with an execution under this Article by any licensed health
24 care professional, including, but not limited to, physicians, nurses, and pharmacists, shall not be
25 cause for any disciplinary or corrective measures by any board, commission, or other authority
26 created by the State or governed by State law which oversees or regulates the practice of health
27 care professionals, including, but not limited to, the North Carolina Medical Board, the North
28 Carolina Board of Nursing, and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy.
29 (b) The infliction of the punishment of death under this Article, including by
30 administration of the required lethal substances under this Article substances, shall not be
31 construed to be the practice of medicine."
32 SECTION 4. G.S. 15-190(a) reads as rewritten:
33 "(a) Correction custody personnel or some other reliable person or persons to be named
34 and designated by the warden from time to time shall cause the person, convict or felon against
35 whom the death sentence has been so pronounced to be executed as provided by this Article and
36 all amendments thereto. The execution shall be under the general supervision and control of the
37 warden of the penitentiary, who shall from time to time, in writing, name and designate the
38 correctional custody personnel or other reliable person or persons who shall cause the person,
39 convict or felon against whom the death sentence has been pronounced to be executed as
40 provided by this Article and all amendments thereto. At such execution there shall be present the
41 warden or deputy warden or some person designated by the warden in the warden's place, and a
42 licensed physician, or a medical professional other than a physician, to monitor the injection of
43 the required lethal substances substances, if any, and certify the fact of the execution. If a licensed
44 physician is not present at the execution, then a licensed physician shall be present on the
45 premises and available to examine the body after the execution and pronounce the person dead.
46 Four respectable citizens, two members of the victim's family, the counsel and any relatives of
47 such person, convict or felon and a minister or member of the clergy or religious leader of the
48 person's choosing may be present if they so desire. The identities, including the names, residential
49 addresses, residential telephone numbers, and social security numbers, of witnesses or persons
50 designated to carry out the execution shall be confidential and exempted from Chapter 132 of the
51 General Statutes and are not subject to discovery or introduction as evidence in any proceeding.
